    {
      "id": "iDegUz9bRt5go-5VOAfGi",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 2750.72192827749,
      "y": -1542.6765873015927,
      "width": 1289.480452674897,
      "height": 2333.680555555555,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#e03131",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b5K",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 823296638,
      "version": 316,
      "versionNonce": 574817854,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1772310193251,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "How to Read This Diagram (The 3 Core Flows)\n1. The Training Flow (Inside the Gym)\n\nYou (the Supervisor) log into the Next.js Frontend.\n\nYou build a Campaign (e.g., \"Hurricane Season\") which saves to\nSupabase.\n\nYou click \"Train.\" The Python API tells agent_builder.py to wrap\nphysics.py and run millions of iterations against that campaign.\n\nOnce the AI survives, the resulting .zip file is saved to the\ndatabase.\n\n2. The Real-World Execution Flow (Inside Prime)\n\nThe trained .zip file is deployed into Petros Prime's \"Reflexes.\"\n\nThe LLM Orchestrator talks to the human: \"I am monitoring\ninventory.\"\n\nThe LLM uses FastMCP Tools to constantly read real-time stock\nlevels from the ERP and check the News/Weather.\n\nWhen it detects a need to buy stock, it runs the numbers\nthrough its Reflexes (.zip), gets the exact mathematically\noptimized quantity, and pushes a Purchase Order back to the\nERP.\n\n3. The \"Digital Twin\" Link (Connecting Prime to Gym)\n\nPetros Prime sees a port strike in the News API.\n\nIt's unsure how the current inventory will handle it. It tells the\nhuman: \"I want to run a simulation.\"\n\nPetros Prime uses its Tools to call the Python Backend API in\nPetros Gym (The \"Digital Twin Link\").\n\nIt passes the company's real-time inventory state and asks the\nGym to run a specific Campaign.\n\nphysics.py runs the simulation, saves the simulation_runs to\nSupabase, and returns a summary to the LLM.\n\nYou (the human) can immediately log into the Next.js Frontend\nand view the newly generated charts of that exact simulation!",
      "fontSize": 39.722222222222214,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "How to Read This Diagram (The 3 Core Flows)\n1. The Training Flow (Inside the Gym)\n\nYou (the Supervisor) log into the Next.js Frontend.\n\nYou build a Campaign (e.g., \"Hurricane Season\") which saves to Supabase.\n\nYou click \"Train.\" The Python API tells agent_builder.py to wrap physics.py and run millions of iterations against that campaign.\n\nOnce the AI survives, the resulting .zip file is saved to the database.\n\n2. The Real-World Execution Flow (Inside Prime)\n\nThe trained .zip file is deployed into Petros Prime's \"Reflexes.\"\n\nThe LLM Orchestrator talks to the human: \"I am monitoring inventory.\"\n\nThe LLM uses FastMCP Tools to constantly read real-time stock levels from the ERP and check the News/Weather.\n\nWhen it detects a need to buy stock, it runs the numbers through its Reflexes (.zip), gets the exact mathematically optimized quantity, and pushes a Purchase Order back to the ERP.\n\n3. The \"Digital Twin\" Link (Connecting Prime to Gym)\n\nPetros Prime sees a port strike in the News API.\n\nIt's unsure how the current inventory will handle it. It tells the human: \"I want to run a simulation.\"\n\nPetros Prime uses its Tools to call the Python Backend API in Petros Gym (The \"Digital Twin Link\").\n\nIt passes the company's real-time inventory state and asks the Gym to run a specific Campaign.\n\nphysics.py runs the simulation, saves the simulation_runs to Supabase, and returns a summary to the LLM.\n\nYou (the human) can immediately log into the Next.js Frontend and view the newly generated charts of that exact simulation!",
      "autoResize": false,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
