      "updated": 1772311058716,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "📞 What-If Scenario\nRequest\n(Verification /\nRetraining Trigger)",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "center",
      "verticalAlign": "middle",
      "containerId": "xBnCQ7DyHNy7BQUhJ2Xf7",
      "originalText": "📞 What-If Scenario Request\n(Verification / Retraining Trigger)",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "enB-vqObf_4OaAlFGvHF0",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 2188.869047619053,
      "y": 3626.3234126984066,
      "width": 1300,
      "height": 1960,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#e03131",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b6A",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 763581438,
      "version": 268,
      "versionNonce": 373930942,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1772311305934,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Detailed Breakdown of the Architecture\n1. The Internals of Petros Prime & How it Achieves RL\n\nThe LLM Orchestrator (The Brain): This is the core reasoning engine. It parses natural\nlanguage from the manager, decides which tools to use, and formulates strategies.\n\nThe RL Inference Engine (The Reflexes): Petros Prime does not train on the fly in the real\nworld—that is far too dangerous for a supply chain. Instead, it loads the graduated .zip\nmodel from Petros Gym. When the LLM realizes a complex logistical decision is needed, it\nformats the current ERP data into a normalized array (e.g., [0.8, 0.2, 0.5, 0.1]), hands it to\nthe RL Engine, and the RL Engine instantly fires back the mathematically optimal action.\n\n2. Where Petros Prime Will Reside\n\nSecure Cloud Hosting: Petros Prime lives in a standard, secure cloud environment (like AWS,\nAzure, or Google Cloud Run). It is built as a \"stateless\" application.\n\nMulti-Tenancy: The Tenant State Manager ensures that when \"Company A\" logs in, the LLM\nonly accesses Company A's data and API keys. The RL .zip model is shared (since it's just a\ngeneralized math formula), but the data passed through it is strictly siloed by your\ndatabase's Row Level Security (RLS).\n\n3. Interaction with External APIs via FastMCP\n\nThe LLM doesn't browse the web directly. It connects to the FastMCP Server, which acts as\na standardized toolbelt.\n\nIf the LLM needs to know the weather, it calls the ToolExt (External Tools) endpoint in\nFastMCP. FastMCP executes the exact Python code to hit the NOAA API and returns the\nstructured data to the LLM.\n\nIf it needs to order stock, it calls ToolERP to execute a POST request to the client's\nactual SAP/Oracle database.\n\n4. Human Interaction via the LLM\n\nThe human interacts exclusively with the LLM via a chat interface. The LLM acts as the\nbilingual translator between the human and the code.\n\nThe manager types: \"How are our inventory levels looking given the incoming storm?\" The LLM\ntranslates this intent, pulls the stock from the FastMCP ERP tool, pulls the storm path from\nthe FastMCP Weather tool, asks the RL Engine for a recommendation, and types back a\nsummarized, conversational answer.\n\n5. The Connection to Petros Gym (Verification/Training)\n\nThis is the ToolGym connection at the bottom right.\n\nScenario Verification: If the LLM reads about a port strike, it can package the company's\ncurrent inventory state, send it across the wire to Petros Gym, and ask the Gym to run a\n30-day simulation. The Gym runs it in physics.py, saves the charts to Supabase, and returns\nthe prediction (e.g., \"90% chance of bankruptcy\").\n\nRetraining Request: If Petros Prime realizes its .zip model is consistently failing in these\nsimulated what-if scenarios, it can use this same link to trigger a new training run in Petros\nGym to generate a smarter .zip file.",
      "fontSize": 28,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Detailed Breakdown of the Architecture\n1. The Internals of Petros Prime & How it Achieves RL\n\nThe LLM Orchestrator (The Brain): This is the core reasoning engine. It parses natural language from the manager, decides which tools to use, and formulates strategies.\n\nThe RL Inference Engine (The Reflexes): Petros Prime does not train on the fly in the real world—that is far too dangerous for a supply chain. Instead, it loads the graduated .zip model from Petros Gym. When the LLM realizes a complex logistical decision is needed, it formats the current ERP data into a normalized array (e.g., [0.8, 0.2, 0.5, 0.1]), hands it to the RL Engine, and the RL Engine instantly fires back the mathematically optimal action.\n\n2. Where Petros Prime Will Reside\n\nSecure Cloud Hosting: Petros Prime lives in a standard, secure cloud environment (like AWS, Azure, or Google Cloud Run). It is built as a \"stateless\" application.\n\nMulti-Tenancy: The Tenant State Manager ensures that when \"Company A\" logs in, the LLM only accesses Company A's data and API keys. The RL .zip model is shared (since it's just a generalized math formula), but the data passed through it is strictly siloed by your database's Row Level Security (RLS).\n\n3. Interaction with External APIs via FastMCP\n\nThe LLM doesn't browse the web directly. It connects to the FastMCP Server, which acts as a standardized toolbelt.\n\nIf the LLM needs to know the weather, it calls the ToolExt (External Tools) endpoint in FastMCP. FastMCP executes the exact Python code to hit the NOAA API and returns the structured data to the LLM.\n\nIf it needs to order stock, it calls ToolERP to execute a POST request to the client's actual SAP/Oracle database.\n\n4. Human Interaction via the LLM\n\nThe human interacts exclusively with the LLM via a chat interface. The LLM acts as the bilingual translator between the human and the code.\n\nThe manager types: \"How are our inventory levels looking given the incoming storm?\" The LLM translates this intent, pulls the stock from the FastMCP ERP tool, pulls the storm path from the FastMCP Weather tool, asks the RL Engine for a recommendation, and types back a summarized, conversational answer.\n\n5. The Connection to Petros Gym (Verification/Training)\n\nThis is the ToolGym connection at the bottom right.\n\nScenario Verification: If the LLM reads about a port strike, it can package the company's current inventory state, send it across the wire to Petros Gym, and ask the Gym to run a 30-day simulation. The Gym runs it in physics.py, saves the charts to Supabase, and returns the prediction (e.g., \"90% chance of bankruptcy\").\n\nRetraining Request: If Petros Prime realizes its .zip model is consistently failing in these simulated what-if scenarios, it can use this same link to trigger a new training run in Petros Gym to generate a smarter .zip file.",
      "autoResize": false,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
