      "text": "📘 Functional Component Breakdown\n1. VPC (Virtual Private Cloud)\nThe Purpose: A logically isolated section of the AWS Cloud where you launch resources.\n\nSenior Insight: Think of this as your \"Data Center in the Cloud.\" At Patriot, you'll likely\nmanage multiple VPCs to isolate Production data from Development data (required for\nSOC2).\n\n2. Subnets (Public vs. Private)\nPublic Subnet: Has a direct route to the Internet Gateway. This is where your Load\nBalancers and NAT Gateways live.\n\nPrivate Subnet: Has no direct route to the internet. This is where your EKS Nodes and\nDatabases live.\n\nThe Flow: Traffic enters the Public subnet (ALB) and is \"proxied\" to the Private subnet.\n\n3. Routing (Route Tables)\nThe Purpose: A set of rules (Destination CIDR -> Target) that tells traffic where to go.\n\nThe Key Rule: Every private subnet needs a route for 0.0.0.0/0 pointing to a NAT Gateway\nso pods can pull updates or talk to external APIs.\n\n4. NAT Gateway (Network Address Translation)\nThe Purpose: Allows resources in a Private Subnet to connect to the internet (outbound)\nbut prevents the internet from initiating a connection to them (inbound).\n\nCost Optimization (JD Mention): NAT Gateways are expensive. A Senior Engineer suggests\nVPC Endpoints for S3 or ECR to bypass the NAT Gateway and save on \"Data Transfer\"\ncosts.\n\n5. VPN (Virtual Private Network)\nThe Purpose: Connects Patriot Software’s office (or a developer's home) to the AWS VPC\nsecurely.\n\nType: Usually a Site-to-Site VPN (connecting an office router to AWS) or Client VPN\n(connecting individual laptops).\n\n6. Transit Gateway (TGW)\nThe Purpose: A network transit hub that you can use to interconnect your VPCs and on-\npremises networks.\n\nWhy it's \"Senior\": Without TGW, if you have 5 VPCs, you have to \"Peer\" them all together in\na messy \"web\" (VPC Peering). TGW acts as a central router, making it easy to share\nservices (like a shared Jenkins or Monitoring tool) across all accounts.",
      "fontSize": 28,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "📘 Functional Component Breakdown\n1. VPC (Virtual Private Cloud)\nThe Purpose: A logically isolated section of the AWS Cloud where you launch resources.\n\nSenior Insight: Think of this as your \"Data Center in the Cloud.\" At Patriot, you'll likely manage multiple VPCs to isolate Production data from Development data (required for SOC2).\n\n2. Subnets (Public vs. Private)\nPublic Subnet: Has a direct route to the Internet Gateway. This is where your Load Balancers and NAT Gateways live.\n\nPrivate Subnet: Has no direct route to the internet. This is where your EKS Nodes and Databases live.\n\nThe Flow: Traffic enters the Public subnet (ALB) and is \"proxied\" to the Private subnet.\n\n3. Routing (Route Tables)\nThe Purpose: A set of rules (Destination CIDR -> Target) that tells traffic where to go.\n\nThe Key Rule: Every private subnet needs a route for 0.0.0.0/0 pointing to a NAT Gateway so pods can pull updates or talk to external APIs.\n\n4. NAT Gateway (Network Address Translation)\nThe Purpose: Allows resources in a Private Subnet to connect to the internet (outbound) but prevents the internet from initiating a connection to them (inbound).\n\nCost Optimization (JD Mention): NAT Gateways are expensive. A Senior Engineer suggests VPC Endpoints for S3 or ECR to bypass the NAT Gateway and save on \"Data Transfer\" costs.\n\n5. VPN (Virtual Private Network)\nThe Purpose: Connects Patriot Software’s office (or a developer's home) to the AWS VPC securely.\n\nType: Usually a Site-to-Site VPN (connecting an office router to AWS) or Client VPN (connecting individual laptops).\n\n6. Transit Gateway (TGW)\nThe Purpose: A network transit hub that you can use to interconnect your VPCs and on-premises networks.\n\nWhy it's \"Senior\": Without TGW, if you have 5 VPCs, you have to \"Peer\" them all together in a messy \"web\" (VPC Peering). TGW acts as a central router, making it easy to share services (like a shared Jenkins or Monitoring tool) across all accounts.",
      "autoResize": false,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
