    {
      "id": "h2U8cmV7t3sMO8z7a5K70",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 12002.502534048901,
      "y": -5290.239087301593,
      "width": 1629.030517578125,
      "height": 2070,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#e03131",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bBX",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 2106691090,
      "version": 174,
      "versionNonce": 1328475726,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1774392046029,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "1. Source → Build (GitLab drives everything)\n\nDevelopers push code to GitLab.\nGitLab CI/CD pipelines build container images and push them to AWS ECR (AWS-native registry)\nand/orHarbor (for added scanning, replication, and policy enforcement).\nThe same pipeline packages deliverables (application code, SBOM for compliance, documentation)\nand uploads them to the proprietary S3 bucket (your deployment endpoint).\n\n2. Authentication Layer (Keycloak everywhere)\n\nKeycloak acts as the central OIDC provider.\nIt provides SSO for:\nGitLab (developers log in)\nAWS EKS (cluster RBAC via OIDC)\nThe public-facing secured web page (users authenticate before downloading files)\n\n\n3. Secrets Management (Secure by Design)\n\nSecrets are stored centrally in AWS Secrets Manager.\nThe AWS External Secrets Operator (running inside EKS) automatically syncs them into Kubernetes\nSecrets.\nPods in EKS can then consume them securely without ever storing secrets in Git or Helm values.\n\n4. Deployment (EKS is the runtime)\n\nEKS pulls the latest images from ECR or Harbor.\nHelm charts (or GitOps) deploy the application.\nThe cluster may optionally reference artifacts from the S3 bucket if needed at runtime.\n\n5. Delivery to Users (Secured Front-End)\n\nThe S3 bucket holds the final installers/docs.\nA secured front-end web page (e.g., static site on S3 + CloudFront, or a small app on EKS) sits in\nfront of it.\nUsers must authenticate via Keycloak before they can download files — keeping everything locked\ndown while still being publicly reachable.\n\nThis setup gives you:\n\nFull CI/CD traceability (GitLab)\nImage security & scanning (Harbor)\nNative AWS container runtime (EKS + ECR)\nZero-trust secrets (Secrets Manager + External Secrets)\nCentralized auth (Keycloak)\nCompliant, auditable delivery (S3 + SBOM)",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "1. Source → Build (GitLab drives everything)\n\nDevelopers push code to GitLab.\nGitLab CI/CD pipelines build container images and push them to AWS ECR (AWS-native registry) and/orHarbor (for added scanning, replication, and policy enforcement).\nThe same pipeline packages deliverables (application code, SBOM for compliance, documentation) and uploads them to the proprietary S3 bucket (your deployment endpoint).\n\n2. Authentication Layer (Keycloak everywhere)\n\nKeycloak acts as the central OIDC provider.\nIt provides SSO for:\nGitLab (developers log in)\nAWS EKS (cluster RBAC via OIDC)\nThe public-facing secured web page (users authenticate before downloading files)\n\n\n3. Secrets Management (Secure by Design)\n\nSecrets are stored centrally in AWS Secrets Manager.\nThe AWS External Secrets Operator (running inside EKS) automatically syncs them into Kubernetes Secrets.\nPods in EKS can then consume them securely without ever storing secrets in Git or Helm values.\n\n4. Deployment (EKS is the runtime)\n\nEKS pulls the latest images from ECR or Harbor.\nHelm charts (or GitOps) deploy the application.\nThe cluster may optionally reference artifacts from the S3 bucket if needed at runtime.\n\n5. Delivery to Users (Secured Front-End)\n\nThe S3 bucket holds the final installers/docs.\nA secured front-end web page (e.g., static site on S3 + CloudFront, or a small app on EKS) sits in front of it.\nUsers must authenticate via Keycloak before they can download files — keeping everything locked down while still being publicly reachable.\n\nThis setup gives you:\n\nFull CI/CD traceability (GitLab)\nImage security & scanning (Harbor)\nNative AWS container runtime (EKS + ECR)\nZero-trust secrets (Secrets Manager + External Secrets)\nCentralized auth (Keycloak)\nCompliant, auditable delivery (S3 + SBOM)",
      "autoResize": false,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
